<article class="article">
  <h2>What is a SIP?</h2>
  <p>A Systematic Investment Plan (SIP) invests a fixed amount into a mutual fund every month, usually by auto-debit. Instead of timing the market, you buy units at whatever the day's NAV is — more units when markets are down, fewer when they are up. Over years, this rupee-cost averaging plus compounding is the most practical wealth-building route for salaried investors, which is why SIPs have become the default way Indians invest in mutual funds.</p>

  <h2>SIP formula</h2>
  <div class="formula">FV = P × ((1 + i)<sup>n</sup> − 1) / i × (1 + i)</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>P</strong> — monthly SIP amount</li>
    <li><strong>i</strong> — monthly return = annual return ÷ 12 ÷ 100</li>
    <li><strong>n</strong> — total number of monthly instalments</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The formula assumes each instalment is invested at the start of the month and compounds monthly at a constant rate. Real fund returns fluctuate, so treat the output as a planning estimate, not a promise.</p>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>
  <p>A ₹10,000 monthly SIP at 12% p.a. for 15 years means i = 0.01 and n = 180. You invest ₹18,00,000 in total, and the formula gives a maturity value of about <strong>₹50.5 lakh</strong> — nearly ₹32.5 lakh of it is growth. Stretch the same SIP to 25 years and the corpus crosses ₹1.9 crore, even though you only invest ₹12 lakh more. The last few years do the heaviest lifting; starting early beats investing more later.</p>

  <h2>How to use this calculator</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Set your monthly amount, expected annual return and time horizon; results update instantly.</li>
    <li>The chart compares your cumulative investment with the growing corpus each year.</li>
    <li>Open the growth table for exact year-end values.</li>
    <li>Planning to raise your SIP every year with your salary? Use the <a href="/step-up-sip-calculator/">Step-Up SIP calculator</a> instead — the difference is dramatic.</li>
  </ul>
</article>

<script>
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function () {
  function recalc() {
    var p = CM.val('p'), rate = CM.val('r'), yrs = CM.val('n');
    var i = rate / 1200, n = Math.round(yrs * 12);
    if (p <= 0 || n <= 0) return;
    var fv = i === 0 ? p * n : p * ((Math.pow(1 + i, n) - 1) / i) * (1 + i);
    var inv = p * n;

    CM.set('out-fv', CM.inr(fv));
    var w = CM.words(fv);
    CM.set('out-fv-sub', w ? 'about ' + w : '');
    CM.set('out-inv', CM.inr(inv));
    CM.set('out-gain', CM.inr(fv - inv));

    var labels = [], invSeries = [], valSeries = [], rows = [];
    var bal = 0;
    for (var mth = 1; mth <= n; mth++) {
      bal = (bal + p) * (1 + i);
      if (mth % 12 === 0 || mth === n) {
        var y = Math.ceil(mth / 12);
        labels.push('Y' + y); invSeries.push(p * mth); valSeries.push(bal);
        rows.push([y, CM.inr(p * mth), CM.inr(bal - p * mth), CM.inr(bal)]);
      }
    }
    CM.lineChart('chart-growth', labels, [
      { label: 'Value', data: valSeries, role: '--s1', fill: true },
      { label: 'Invested', data: invSeries, role: '--s2' }
    ]);
    CM.table('sched-out', ['Year', 'Invested', 'Gain', 'Value'], rows);
  }
  CM.bind(['p', 'r', 'n'], recalc);
});
</script>
